1. ne forte aedas. The addition of forte renders it clear that this is a final clause and not a prohibition. ‘Lest you should think, as rhaps you might...(remember that) Pindar and Simonides are still amous.’ Wickham quotes Epist. 1. 1. 13 Ac ne forte roges quo me duce, quo lare, tuter.- Nullius addictus iurare in verba magistri, Quo me cu ue rapit tempestas, deferor hospes (cf. also Sat. 11. 1. 80, Epist. 11. 1. 208 . It is not however to be supposed that a prohibition would require ne credideris. See the note on Albi, ne doleas 1. 33. 1.
